<HL>
   Bank-Failure Rate Has Slowed Sharply
   This Year, Chairman of the FDIC Says
   ----
   By Paul Duke Jr. and Paulette Thomas
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Bank failures have slowed considerably this
year, said William Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp.
   As of Tuesday, 52 banks with assets of $4.7 billion had
failed in 1990. By contrast, at this time last year, 73 banks
with $19.7 billion in assets had failed or received FDIC
assistance in order to continue operating, Mr. Seidman said.
No banks have received such FDIC aid this year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last year's figures included 20 bank subsidiaries of
Dallas-based MCorp, with assets of $15.6 billion. For all of
last year, 207 banks with $29 billion in assets failed or
were assisted by the FDIC.
   Mr. Seidman said in an interview that initial figures show
the FDIC's bank deposit-insurance fund had a loss of about
$800 million last year, larger than the $250 million-to-$500
million loss he predicted late last year. He said the larger
loss stemmed from greater-than-expected costs from the MCorp
failures and from the failure this year of Seamen's Bank for
Savings, based in New York. (Under its accounting rules, the
FDIC must account for some of those costs in its 1989
results.)
   That loss will leave the deposit-insurance fund with about
$13.2 billion, or about 0.7% of insured deposits. Government
policy is to try to maintain the fund at about 1.25% of
insured deposits. Final figures on the fund's performance
last year are to be released May 18.
   Mr. Seidman said the fund could increase somewhat during
this year, but the failure of a large bank would probably
cause a loss. He wouldn't say whether he was expecting a
large bank failure.
   Mr. Seidman, who is also chairman of the Resolution Trust
Corp., said the RTC may abandon its policy that permits
buyers of insolvent thrifts to repudiate rates paid on
certificates of deposit after two weeks. The RTC is the
agency charged with selling or liquidating hundreds of
insolvent thrifts taken over by the government.
   In a meeting scheduled for May 18, the agency will
consider requiring buyers to honor CD rates for three months,
he said. The policy has recently been recommended to the RTC
board by its staff, he said.
   The move would mean that buyers of insolvent thrifts would
know exactly the cost of funds from the market, Mr. Seidman
said, and that depositors -- often big-deposit brokers --
would have the assurance that their rates would be locked in
for at least 90 days after the thrift is sold. Depositors,
for example, would be able to compare rates at insolvent
thrifts with those of 90-day Treasury instruments, he said.
   Eliminating the uncertainty ultimately means lower costs
for obtaining funds and greater liquidity, Mr. Seidman said.
"If someone has uncertainty, they are going to require a
higher rate," he said.
   Mr. Seidman said the RTC's ambitious project to sell about
140 thrifts by the end of June to get the troubled
thrift-industry bailout off the ground is "on schedule."
   He said sales of assets separately from thrift
institutions were also moving forward, with about $600
million in sales last month. But he said rising interest
rates may make such asset sales more difficult in coming
weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900510-0116
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900510-0116.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Lindner-Run Firm
   Is Seeking Buyers
   For Radio Stations
   ----
   By Kevin Goldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   GACC SP
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Great American Communications Co. is quietly shopping
around some of its radio properties.
   The move, by the Cincinnati company run by financier Carl
H. Lindner, underscores the pressure for cash facing the
highly leveraged company. Great American, which purchased
Taft Broadcasting Co. in October 1987 for about $1.5 billion,
had a $115.6 million loss in 1989 on revenue of $300.6
million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Great American's long-term debt as of Dec. 31 totaled
$1.19 billion. In October, the company will have to pay $165
million as its first principal payments on that debt.
According to several individuals in the radio industry, Great
American would like to raise about $150 million in the sale
of the radio stations.
   The company owns 11 FM stations, six AM stations and five
network-affiliated TV stations. None of the television
stations are for sale. It also has a controlling interest in
Spelling Entertainment Inc., which produced such TV shows as
"The Love Boat" and "Dynasty," and Hanna-Barbera Productions
Inc., the producers of such animated shows as "The
Flintstones" and "The Jetsons."
   Carl J. Wagner, president of Great American Broadcasting
Co., a unit of Great American, couldn't be reached to
comment. However, several people close to the process said
Great American is interested in selling stations in Atlanta,
Kansas City, Mo., Columbus, Ohio, and Indianapolis. One
person with knowledge of the situation said that New York
radio broker Gary Stevens is handling the bidding for the
radio stations.
   Mr. Stevens declined to comment.
   "Great American will sell some media properties," said one
person. "Ultimately, it may not be the radio stations, but
something will go."
   Great American is asking from $50 million to $60 million
for its Atlanta FM station, $50 million for the Indianapolis
AM-FM properties, from $25 million to $30 million for
Columbus AM-FM stations, and about $30 million for the Kansas
City AM-FM properties.
   One person close to the process said Great American "is
pretty firm on these prices at this point. They're
independent thinkers and if they don't get the price they
want, they won't sell."
   There are other options to raise cash.
   In October, Spelling Entertainment put itself on the block
six months after control of the company went from founder
Aaron Spelling to Mr. Lindner. Spelling Entertainment
retained Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.'s Capital Markets unit and
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. to handle the possible sale.
   To date, Spelling Entertainment hasn't been sold. And it
isn't clear what price Spelling Entertainment could fetch.
   Spelling Entertainment has a library of one-hour
prime-time series, such as "Charlie's Angels" and "Hotel."
Such shows have recently not sold well in syndication, the
traditionally lucrative marketplace where shows are sold to
individual stations. Half-hour situation comedies now are the
hot properties in syndication sales to local stations.
   In over-the-counter trading yesterday, Great American rose
37.5 cents to close at $6.625.
</TEXT>
