   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                    MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stanislaus County Waste to Energy Finance Agency, Calif.
-- $92.3 million of waste-energy revenue bonds, due Jan. 1,
1992-1999, 2005 and 2010, were tentatively priced by a
Prudential-Bache Capital Funding group to yield from 6.60% in
1992 to 7.81% in 2010. Current interest serial bonds are
priced to yield from 6.60% in 1992 to 7.50% in 1999. There
are $10 million of 7 5/8% term bonds priced at 99.25 to yield
7.71% in 2005 and $64.9 million of 7 3/4% term bonds priced
at 99.39 to yield 7.81% in 2010. The bonds are rated triple-B
by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   Delaware -- $65 million of general obligation bonds due
May 1, 1991-2010, apparently were won by a Manufacturers
Hanover Securities Corp. group with a bid setting the net
interest cost at 6.912911%. The bonds, rated double-A by
Moody's Investors Service Inc. and double-A-plus by S&amp;P, were
priced for reoffering to yield from 6.00% in 1991 to 7.20% in
2009 and 2010. There are no term bonds.
                                                                                                       

                       MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $500 million of real
estate mortgage investment conduit securities is being
offered in nine classes by Salomon Brothers Inc. The
offering, Series 174, is backed by Freddie Mac 10%
securities. Details on yields weren't immediately available.
   UBS Securities Inc. -- $300.3 million of UBS Trust 5 Remic
securities is being offered in 13 classes. The offering is
backed by Government National Mortgage Association 9 1/2%
securities. For classes with details available, yields range
from 9.29% to 10.15%. The issue is rated triple-A by S&amp;P and
Moody's.

                      ASSET-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Rochester Community Savings Bank -- $125 million of
certificates backed by automobile and light-truck loans with
a coupon rate of 9 1/4% at 99 33/64 to yield 9.51% through
First Boston Corp. The issue, through RCSB 1990-A Grantor
Trust, was priced at a yield spread of 0.79 percentage point
above the Treasury two-year note. The issue has an estimated
average life of 1.88 years, assuming monthly prepayments at
1.3% of the original loan balance. The legal final maturity
date is Nov. 11, 1995. The issue is rated triple-A by
Moody's, based on the quality of the underlying auto and
light-truck loans and a letter of credit covering 12% of the
deal from Credit Suisse. There is no guarantee from Rochester
Community Savings Bank on the issue. A First Boston official
said the issue was all sold.
                                                                                                       

