<HL>
   Technology Brief -- Pioneer Electronic Corp.:
   Satellite Navigation System
   Is Developed for Vehicles
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   PIO
</CO>
<LP>
   A new navigation system made by Pioneer Electronic Corp.
of Japan uses satellites to calculate a vehicle's location
and then displays it to the driver on maps on a small color
screen.
   The system, which goes on sale in Japan next month,
connects to a vehicle's audio system and uses special compact
disks to display maps of any part of Japan, Pioneer spokesman
Toru Yokomizo said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   He said it is the first satellite navigation system for
cars available as an accessory on the retail market.
   The device, named AVIC-1, can be used by cars, trucks or
helicopters while in motion or standing still, Mr. Yokomizo
said.
   The complete system, including navigation device, display,
antenna and audio system, will cost about 500,000 yen
($3,200), he said.
</TEXT>
