<HL>
   French Economic Forecast
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARIS -- France's total output of goods and services is
likely to continue expanding at an annual rate of between 2%
and 3% in the first half of 1990 on a market basis, little
changed from the pace recorded in the second half of 1989,
the National Statistics Institute said.
   The French gross national product grew 4.1% on a market
basis and 3.7% overall in 1989. The former figure only takes
into account market activity, thereby excluding certain
government transactions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   French government forecasters in the Economics Ministry
said last month that GNP in 1990 would rise 3.2%.
   Inflation, meanwhile, is expected to ease to an annual
rate of 3.1% by June, down from 3.4% in March, helped by
lower petroleum and food prices, as well as the stronger
franc, which lowered the cash cost of imports in the short
term.
</TEXT>
