<DOCNO>
WSJ900510-0037
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900510-0037.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Market Ends Lower on Refunding Fears;
   FNB Rochester Up 2 1/4 on Buy-Out News
   ----
   By Anne Newman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Over-the-counter stocks ended their seven-day streak of
advances with a slight loss as investors kept a cautious eye
on the unfolding quarterly Treasury refunding.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index eased 0.12%, slipping 0.50 to
431.34. Declining shares overtook advancing stocks, 1,013 to
898, as 99 issues dropped to new lows while 90 reached new
highs. Volume picked up to 146.6 million shares from 133.8
million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Peter Da Puzzo, co-head of world-wide equity operations
for Shearson Lehman Hutton, said that he was encouraged by
the market's late afternoon recovery as it became apparent
the auction of 10-year Treasury notes was successful. The
composite index hit an intraday low of 430.82 before firming
slightly.
   Mr. Da Puzzo suggests that today will be quiet, as
investors pull back and wait for the auction of 30-year
Treasury bonds and tomorrow's figures on retail sales and the
producer price index. "The 30-year auction will be key to
what happens in the equity market," he noted. He remains
bullish about both secondary and blue-chip stocks, predicting
the Dow Jones Industrial Average will hit a record high this
summer.
   The technology sector remained in vogue, with Sun
Microsystems in the forefront. Sun rose 2 1/2 to 28 3/8 on
5.3 million shares after this newspaper reported the Mountain
View, Calif., concern is expected to unveil a new low-cost
computer workstation next week.
   Among other technology shares, Intel rose 1/4 to 43 1/4,
Oracle Systems climbed 1/4 to 18 1/8 and Seagate Technology
was unchanged at 12 1/4. The Nasdaq 100 Index of industrial
stocks, including many large technology issues, rose 0.52, or
0.12%, to 430.86.
   Investors embraced an initial public offering of 1.87
million shares of RasterOps, a Santa Clara, Calif., designer
and maker of color imaging products. Offered at $12 a share,
the stock remained unchanged at 14 7/8, with more than two
million shares changing hands.
   National Media was among the day's most-active issues,
rising 1/2 to 9 3/4 on 1.3 million shares. Stephen Axelrod,
analyst at Denver-based Stuart James, raised his earnings
estimates for the Philadelphia provider of direct-marketing
services. According to Dow Jones Professional Investor
Report, Mr. Axelrod cited the company's success with a new
television marketing format in his estimate that National
Media will report earnings of $1 a share for the year ended
March 31 and his projection of $1.50 to $2.50 a share in
fiscal 1991.
   Shares of McCaw Cellular Communications, which acquired
52% of LIN Broadcasting, closed off 1/4 at 23 1/2 on more
than four times average volume. Tuesday, LIN Broadcasting,
agreed to acquire Metromedia Inc.'s cellular operations in
New York for $1.9 billion in cash and preferred stock. The
transaction will add more than $1 billion in debt to LIN's
balance sheet. LIN also reported a $180.8 million
first-quarter loss after taking a charge of nearly $300
million for executive severance payments and other costs.
   News of mergers or potential buy-outs fueled gains in
stocks of three northeastern concerns: FNB Rochester rose 2
1/4 to 13 1/2; Lexington Savings climbed 1 1/4 to 8, and
Aritech gained 3/4 to 11 3/4.
   FNB Rochester, a Rochester, N.Y., holding company for the
First National Bank of Rochester and Atlanta (N.Y.) National
Bank, said that a diversified Turkish concern, Cukurova
Holding AS Group, agreed to buy 75% of its outstanding common
stock at $20 a share. The company announced May 1 that it had
received an unsolicited offer.
   Waltham Savings Bank, Waltham, Mass., announced it that
will acquire Lexington Savings, Lexington, Mass., for $10.75
a share. The combined banks are expected to have total assets
of $700 million. Lexington Savings also reported a loss for
the first quarter ended March 31 of six cents a share, after
a $975,000 provision for loan losses, compared with net
income of 17 cents a share a year earlier.
   Aritech gained 3/4 to 11 3/4 after the Framingham, Mass.,
maker of burglar alarm systems said late Tuesday that a
special committee of outside directors will review the
possible sale of the company to management or a third party.
On May 3, Aritech announced it hired an investment adviser to
explore ways to improve shareholders' value.
   Kustom Electronics advanced 5/8 to 4 7/8 after the
Overland, Kan., maker of traffic safety radar systems and
other communications equipment said that Triax International
agreed to buy its traffic safety unit for $4.3 million in
cash and a $700,000 promissory note to be paid over three
years.
   Shares of Millicom, a New York maker of cellular mobile
communications systems, advanced 1 1/4 to 19 1/2. The Federal
Communications Commission issued Millicom's PCN America unit
experimental licenses to build and operate its Personal
Communications Networks in Houston and Orlando, Fla.
   Mesa Airlines rose 7/8 to 8 3/8 after the Farmington,
N.M., commuter airline reported net income for the second
quarter ended March 31 of 28 cents a share, up from 10 cents
a year earlier.
   Comair Holdings, which rose 1 1/4 Tuesday, closed off 1/4
at 17 3/8 after the Cincinnati airline reported that April
traffic rose 40.8% since April 1989.
   Among the day's losers was Quiksilver, which slipped 7/8
to 26 5/8 after this newspaper's Inside Track column reported
that the Costa Mesa, Calif., concern was one of three apparel
companies whose executives and directors sold more than
100,000 shares in the first quarter. The Quiksilver insiders
sold a total of 130,000 shares at prices ranging from $23.53
to $25.38 a share. The company declined comment.
   Kulicke &amp; Soffa Industries fell 1/4 to 9 1/4 after the
Willow Grove, Pa., maker of semiconductor assembly systems
reported Tuesday a loss for the second quarter which ended
March 31 of 39 cents a share, compared with net income of 11
cents a share a year earlier. The most recent quarter
included a $3.9 million increase in reserves for inventories,
a $900,000 charge for organizational changes and legal fees
and an extraordinary gain of $129,000.
</TEXT>
