<HL>
   Legg Mason Joins
   Regional Brokers
   With Record Profit
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   RJF AGE LM
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Here are two words not often heard on Wall
Street these days: record earnings.
   But several smaller regional securities firms -- including
Legg Mason Inc., A.G. Edwards Inc. and Raymond James
Financial Inc. -- posted record revenue and earnings for past
12 months. Regionals typically are based far from New York
and focus more on clients around the corner than around the
globe.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Yesterday, Legg Mason reported a 75% jump in net income
for its fiscal fourth quarter ended March 31, and a 97% rise
for the fiscal year, capping relatively robust returns for
the nation's regional securities firms -- and a far cry from
the woes engulfing many big national brokerage firms.
   The regionals "continue to add to their sales forces and
bring in more customers," says Perrin Long, senior securities
analyst for Lipper Analytical Securities Corp. "At most
regional firms, revenues are rising more rapidly than
expenses."
   Legg Mason's results underscore the good news at many
small regional concerns. Their brokerage business serving
individual investors and their investment advisory business,
particularly mutual funds, are prospering, compared with a
lackluster year-earlier period. The improvement in Legg
Mason's retail, or individual-investor, segment reflected a
"modest increase" in the number of the firm's brokers and a
jump in average revenue per broker. And revenue from Legg
Mason's investment advisory business, primarily mutual funds,
rose 22% from a year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter net at the Baltimore-based securities firm
was $1.7 million, or 20 cents a share, up from $951,000, or
11 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 10% to $58.7
million from $53.2 million.
   Not all regional securities firms have prospered recently.
Net in the most recent quarter fell 19% at Piper Jaffray
Inc., for example. And some big securities firms,
particularly Morgan Stanley Group Inc., are thriving even
amid the current Wall Street recession.
   But it generally has been tougher going for most
full-service national brokerage firms, many of whom have been
sharply cutting back staff. The big securities firms have
been hit hard by a slowdown in investment banking
revenue-down more than 20% at many big firms. And the
investment-banking slump was offset at some firms only by fat
trading gains, which can't be counted on to continue.
   Regional firms, however, are much more dependent on the
activity of individual investors; indeed, their performance
is often viewed as a gauge of small-investor interest in the
stock market. And despite their recent rebound, regional
firms' net income still stands at just half its peak in 1986.
In 1989, regionals' net doubled to $215 million but was still
well below 1986's record $546 million, according to the
Securities Industry Association.
   Regionals face stiffer competition, moreover, from some
full-service national firms such as Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. that are redirecting their energies back to serving
individual investors. Still, regionals have a head start in
courting the little guy, cutting costs and focusing on a few
profitable businesses.
   Regionals "already are well on their way -- if they're not
already niche firms," says Alison Deans, an analyst at Smith
Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. "They're sticking to their
strengths and keeping costs low."
   Legg Mason stock fell 12.5 cents to close at $13.125 a
share in New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900510-0017
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900510-0017.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   Treasury's Sale of 10-Year Notes Is Big Success
   As Investors Flock to Get 8.88% Average Yield
   ----
   By Constance Mitchell and Susan Scherreik
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<CO>
   FRE RCSB JAPAN EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The Treasury's 10-year note auction was a big
success, drawing unexpectedly strong demand from
institutional and individual investors who were attracted by
the best yields in a year.
   "It was a very strong auction," said Thomas Pura, a
partner at Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. "Investors find securities
attractive at these levels."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury sold $10 billion of the new 10-year notes at
an average yield of 8.88%. That was much higher than the
average yield of 8.59% at the previous 10-year note auction
in February and the highest yield at an auction since 9.18%
last May.
   Yesterday's sale was the second part of the Treasury's
three-part $30.5 billion quarterly refunding of the federal
debt. The Treasury sold $10.5 billion of three-year notes on
Tuesday and will conclude the auction with the sale of $10
billion of 30-year bonds today.
   Mr. Pura said yesterday's auction, coming on top of a
strong three-year note auction on Tuesday, increases the odds
that today's 30-year bond sale will go smoothly.
   Bond dealers said that all types of investors -- large,
small, domestic and foreign -- were eager to buy the
Treasury's new 10-year notes.
   F. Ward McCarthy, managing director at Stone &amp; McCarthy
Research Associates, said that investors were especially
happy because yields at the auction were just high enough for
the Treasury to set a 8 7/8% coupon rate on the notes.
   "If the average yield had been one basis point (one
one-hundredth of a percentage point) lower, the coupon would
have been set at 8 3/4%. That one basis point was important
and made the notes more attractive to the investment
community," said Mr. McCarthy.
   Michael Moore, manager of government trading at
Continental Bank, said investors eager to buy the 10-year
notes spent much of the morning session selling 30-year,
seven-year and five-year Treasury securities "to make room
for the new 10-year." He said demand for the 10-year notes
was strong because the yield was relatively high compared to
yields on some other Treasury securities.
   The success of the auction was clearly unexpected. Traders
said that some dealers, expecting only moderate or even weak
demand for the 10-year notes, placed bids that were too low
and subsequently did not get enough securities to meet
customer orders. Mr. McCarthy estimates that only 33% of the
major New York dealers that tendered bids were actually
awarded bonds.
   As a result, some firms were forced to scramble to buy the
new 10-year Treasury notes in the secondary market. Evidence
of that was apparent in the unusually heavy trading activity
in the new 10-year note by interdealer brokers,
intermediaries that buy and sell securities for the 44
primary dealers of government bonds. Interdealer brokers do
not trade with the general public.
   Traders said about $1 billion of the notes were exchanged
in when-issued trading activity at yields of 8.85% to 8.86%,
far below the auction rates. Of that amount, $630 million was
said to have been traded by RMJ Securities Corp., one of the
five major interdealer brokers. RMJ declined to comment.
   Individual investors, who purchased a record amount of
three-year notes at Tuesday's sale, also showed a hearty
appetite for the new 10-year notes.
   Individual investors typically buy securities at Treasury
auctions through noncompetitive tenders, which totaled $659
million at the 10-year note sale. That was well above the
average noncompetitive bids of $427 million at the previous
12 auctions, according to Maria Ramirez Capital Consultants
Inc.
   The last time noncompetitive bids at a 10-year auction
were higher than yesterday was in August 1985, according to
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., when noncompetitive tenders
totaled $686 million.
   Japanese investors, as expected, bought large amounts of
the 10-year notes. A trader at one of Japan's largest
securities firm estimates that the Japanese purchased about
30% of the new 10-year notes.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices moved sharply lower ahead of the government's
10-year note auction, as dealers cut prices in an effort to
drum up demand for the government's new securities.
   Traders said the market's weakness ahead of auction also
reflected higher commodity prices, a weaker dollar on foreign
exchange markets and a large sale of mortgage-backed
securities by the Resolution Trust Corp. RTC, the government
agency created to bailout the nation's troubled savings and
loan associations, could not be reached for comment.
   Analysts said the RTC sale depressed the market because
buyers of the securities had to sell Treasurys to hedge their
purchase of mortgage-backed securities.
   Treasury bond prices received a modest boost late
yesterday as dealers scrambled to buy new 10-year notes in
when-issued trading activity. But the lift wasn't large
enough to offset the large declines that occurred earlier in
the day.
   The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, which was quoted as
much as 3/4 point lower in early trading, ended about 1/2
point lower. The bond was quoted late at a price of 96 2/32
to yield 8.86% compared with 96 16/32 to yield 8.82%.
   Short-term rates were slightly lower. The rates on
three-month Treasury bills was 7.75% for a bond equivalent
yield of 7.99% while the rate on six-month bills eased
slightly to 7.77% for a bond-equivalent yield of 8.18%.
   Here are details of yesterday's 10-year note auction:
                                                                                                       

   Rates are determined by the difference between the
purchase price and face value. Thus, higher bidding narrows
the investor's return while lower bidding widens it.
                                                                                                       

   Applications ............................ $30,041,819,000
   Accepted bids ........................... $10,025,742,000
   Accepted at low price ...................             63%
   Accepted noncompetitively ...............    $659,000,000
   Average price (Rate) ....................  99.967 (8.88%)
   High price (Rate) ....................... 100.033 (8.87%)
   Low price (Rate) ........................  99.967 (8.88%)
   Interest rate ...........................          8 7/8%
                                                                                                       

   The notes are dated May 15 and mature May 15, 2000.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage securities ended 7/32 to 9/32 lower in moderate
trading.
   Government National Mortgage Association's 9% securities
for May delivery finished at 94 1/4, down 9/32. The agency's
9 1/2% issue was at 96 25/32, down 8/32, and its 10% issue
was quoted at 99 7/32, down 8/32. Federal Home Loan Mortgage
Corp.'s 9 1/2% issue ended at 96 18/32, down 7/32.
   The Ginnie Mae 9% issue was yielding 9.99% to a 12-year
average life assumption.
   In the derivative markets, Freddie Mac issued a $500
million real estate mortgage investment conduit, or Remic,
backed by its 10% securities through Salomon Brothers Inc.
UBS Securities Inc. offered $300 million of Remic securities
backed by Ginnie Mae's 9 1/2% issue.
   In the asset-backed market, Rochester Community Savings
Bank offered about $125 million of certificates backed by
automobile and light-truck loans at a yield of 9.51% through
First Boston Corp.
   The issue by the Rochester, N.Y.-based savings bank was
rated triple-A by Moody's Investors Service Inc.
                                                                                                       

   Junk Bonds

   Trump Plaza junk bonds climbed yesterday after The Wall
Street Journal's "Heard on the Street" column reported that
some bargain hunters are buying the bonds.
   Trump Plaza is one of several Atlantic City casinos
operated by real estate developer Donald Trump. The Plaza's
12 7/8% bonds maturing in 1998 gained 1 1/2 to end at 83.
Other Trump junk bonds, including the Trump Taj Mahal Funding
and Trump Castle Funding, showed little change.
   Most junk bonds, or speculative-grade securities with low
credit ratings or no credit ratings at all, ended unchanged
to about 1/4 point higher.
   Investment-grade corporate bonds were 1/8 to 1/4 point
lower.
                                                                                                       

   Municipal Issues
                                                                                                       

   Municipal issues fell 3/8 point in quiet dealings but the
market still feels positive, according to traders.
   "Retail is still buying bonds," one trader said. He
attributed the lack of activity to investors waiting for the
outcome of the final leg of the Treasury refunding today.
   An unsold balance of $17.8 million remained on an $65
million issue of Delaware general obligation bonds won by a
Manufacturers Securities Inc. group. The bonds were priced
for reoffering to yield from 6% in 1991 to 7.20% in 2009 and
2010.
   Among dollar bonds, the New Jersey Turnpike Authority's
7.20% issue due in 2018 were 3/8 lower at 96 1/4 to yield
7.50%.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   A stronger yen and falling money market rates pushed up
Japanese government bond prices.
   The dollar ended at 157.03 yen in Tokyo, down from 157.63
yen in late New York trading and 158.05 yen at the Tokyo
close on Tuesday.
   But dealers don't expect the yen's firmness to last. They
say that after this week's $30.5 billion U.S. Treasury
refunding that the demand for dollars will increase among
Japanese investors who have bought the new Treasury issues.
   Elsewhere, West Germany government bonds rose when
international investors, long absent from the market, rushed
to buy mark bonds.
   "There's a bit of a positive sentiment in this market and
no selling except for some domestic investors taking
profits," said a West German bond trader. "And that seems to
be drying up."
   Bonn's 7 3/4% issue due in 2000 rose 0.35 point to 95.20
to yield 8.48%, while its 8% notes due in 1995 jumped 0.25
point to 96.60 to yield 8.89%.
   Bond prices fell in Britain.
</TEXT>
