<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE DOLLAR SKIDDED on speculation that Washington's effort
to cut the budget deficit may push U.S. interest rates lower.
The currency fell to a 28-month low against the mark. Bond
prices also dropped despite a good response to the Treasury's
$10 billion auction of 10-year notes. Stock prices closed
mixed.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Budget talks will begin Tuesday between Bush and top
congressional leaders. But the administration insisted the
president hasn't given up his opposition to tax increases.
   ---
   Competition is heating up again in international express
delivery. JAL, Lufthansa and Nissho Iwai are seeking equity
ties with DHL Worldwide Express, putting more pressure on
Federal Express and UPS, which are pushing hard to expand
overseas.
   ---
   Ford's patent-infringement case involving windshield
wipers was deadlocked over damages. A new jury will decide
how much the auto maker should pay inventor Robert Kearns.
   ---
   Mattel announced its first quarterly dividend in seven
years and said it plans to repay $75 million in senior notes,
reflecting improved earnings. The toy maker also announced a
licensing agreement involving the hit TV cartoon series "The
Simpsons."
   ---
   Interco said it won't pay interest due June 15 on its
bonds, proposing instead that bondholders accept a $900
million debt restructuring. Analysts view the plan as a first
step in what may be a long series of negotiations.
   ---
   Prices for summer travel aren't going up despite increased
airline traffic and hotel occupancy rates. Many travel
companies don't want to risk boosting prices because the
market is still relatively soft.
   ---
   Inflation may be worse than recent statistics indicate,
economists say. They cite hard-to-measure, extra-inflationary
forces such as higher property and local taxes, soaring
health costs and increasing tuition fees.
   ---
   Major TV networks are hoping to scrap the long-standing
practice of guaranteeing advertisers a certain number of
viewers. But the effort, reflecting a shrinking TV audience,
is being resisted by the ad industry.
   ---
   Bank failures have slowed considerably this year,
according to FDIC Chairman William Seidman. As of Tuesday, 52
banks had failed in 1990, compared with 73 that failed or got
FDIC aid at this time last year.
   ---
   Investor choices in arbitrating disputes with brokers were
narrowed by a federal appeals court. The court said investors
nationwide can be required to arbitrate in New York rather
than their hometown.
   ---
   Money market-fund assets fell for the sixth week in a row
as investors found other places to put their cash.
   ---
   Kodak expects improved sales and earnings this year after
a bleak 1989. The photography giant also plans an aggressive
expansion into Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 152,220,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2732.88, off 0.68; transportation 1161.45, off 3.56;
utilities 213.78, up 1.69.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3276.93, off
10.43.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 135.14, up 1.47; spot
index 135.60, up 0.55.
   Dollar: 156.50 yen, off 1.12; 1.6360 marks, off 0.0213.
