<HL>
   Foreign Exchange:
   U.S. Unit Plunges to a 28-Month Low
   Against Mark on Interest-Rate Jitters
   ----
   By John Bader
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST JAPAN EUROP CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The dollar declined sharply against major
currencies yesterday amid fears that current efforts to
reduce the federal budget deficit might result in downward
pressure on U.S. interest rates.
   The U.S. unit fell two pfennigs to a 28-month low against
the mark and dropped more than a yen as a budget "summit" was
scheduled for Tuesday between President Bush and Congress.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Some participants said the dollar's sharp decline was
precipitated by an article yesterday in The Wall Street
Journal suggesting that Mr. Bush sees an accord on narrowing
the deficit as the only way to ensure lower interest rates
over the long term.
   The administration is known to favor lower interest rates
as a means of stimulating the economy and spurring
improvement in the country's trade imbalance with Japan,
which recent dollar strength against the yen is seen
impeding.
   During the afternoon, the White House released a statement
saying it hoped an agreement on the budget deficit would lead
the Federal Reserve Bank to reduce interest rates. "We would
hope that the Fed would be impressed" with the latest effort
to cut the deficit, said White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   The budget talks were scheduled amid some disappointment
in the market at the 8.74% average yield that the Treasury's
$10.5 billion of three-year notes brought Tuesday, said David
Ogg, chief dealer at Credit Suisse in New York. The market
had been hoping for a slightly higher yield to serve as a
sign that pressure for lower U.S. interest rates isn't
growing, Mr. Ogg said.
   News that the Treasury's $10 billion of 10-year notes
brought an average yield of 8.88% yesterday came too late in
the day to influence currency trading.
   Traders said earlier yesterday that they would be watching
the 10-year note auction later in the day and the 30-year
bond sale today in order to gauge foreign investors'
confidence in the U.S.
   Japanese participation in both Tuesday's and yesterday's
note auctions ran at about the customary 30% level, according
to preliminary information. Traders said they are most
interested in Japanese purchases of 10-year and 30-year
paper, reasoning that good buying by Japanese of the
longer-term issues signals stronger willingness to invest in
U.S. paper.
   In late New York trading yesterday, the dollar was quoted
at 1.6360 marks, down from 1.6573 marks late Tuesday, and at
156.50 yen, down from 157.62 yen late Tuesday. Sterling was
quoted at $1.6785, up from $1.6705 Tuesday.
   In early trading in Tokyo Thursday, the U.S. currency was
quoted at 156.55 yen, down from Wednesday's Tokyo close of
157.03 yen. Meanwhile, the dollar was trading at about 1.6355
marks.
   Overall, the market remains bearish on the dollar in the
short term, with participants choosing to view developments
with an eye toward selling the U.S. unit, said Robert White,
a vice president and manager of corporate trading at First
Interstate Bank of California in Los Angeles.
   Mr. White cited as evidence the market's reaction to the
budget-deficit talks. Traders focused on the possibility of
lower interest rates that the discussions might produce
instead of on prospects for a reduction in the deficit, which
could be seen as bullish for the dollar, Mr. White said.
   The U.S. unit's fall against the mark was exacerbated by
growing demand for the West German unit based on an improving
market assessment of the West German central bank's ability
to control inflation associated with German reunification,
said Andy Robertson, foreign exchange sales manager at Chase
Manhattan Bank in New York.
   The mark also recorded gains against the yen in active
non-dollar dealings yesterday, rising to 95.63 yen in late
New York trading from 95.10 yen in New York Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current
delivery rose $1.90 to $371.90 an ounce in moderate trading.
Estimated volume was 3.6 million ounces.
   In Hong Kong Thursday, gold was quoted at $371 an ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900510-0005
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900510-0005.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Enterprise:
   Players Club Sees a Good Bet in Niche Left by Casinos
   ---
   Company Seeks to Treat Medium-Stakes
   Gamblers Like High Rollers
   ----
   By Pauline Yoshihashi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   PLAY
</CO>
<IN>
CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)
CORPORATE PROFILE (PRO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Players International Inc. is cashing in on gambling
without the help of dice, cards or slot machines.
   The small company's five-year-old Players Club, endorsed
on late-night cable television by the actor Telly Savalas,
promises medium-stakes gamblers a taste of the red-carpet
treatment that casinos usually reserve for high rollers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Most people love a bargain, and Players promises discounts
on casino hotel rooms, food and shows, along with other
perks, in such gambling meccas as Las Vegas, Atlantic City,
N.J., and the Bahamas. Some joiners say it doesn't pay. But
the club says many members recoup the $125-a-year membership
fee in a single outing, saving 25% to 60% on air fare,
lodging, food and entertainment.
   Like many new companies, Players aims to capitalize on an
opening left by larger ones. Casinos work hard to bring in
busloads of penny-pinching slot-machine players and to
attract $40,000-a-hand baccarat aficionados and other high
rollers. Players Club is aimed at millions of so-called
middle-market gamblers, who it says are often overlooked by
casino marketing programs. Casinos say the middle market is
so diverse that such gamblers are harder to target.
   In return for steering customers to casinos, Players gets
discount rates on blocks of rooms reserved for its members.
The firm spends $6 million to $7 million annually on ads and
marketing, mostly aimed at attracting new members.
   Players Club has expanded to 90,000 members; it says about
5,500 people join each month. Players International says it
expects to report revenue of more than $16 million for the
fiscal year ended March 31, up from $12 million a year
earlier. Besides running the club, the company's activities
include promoting gambling cruises and other travel for
gamblers and arranging casino promotions.
   But Players still has problems. With membership swelling,
each member faces more competition to get one of the rooms
reserved for the club. Thus, more members are likely to be
disappointed -- which hardly sits well with those who signed
up to be coddled. But the main reason about 40% of Players'
members fail to renew is because they don't use them enough.
   In any case, some industry observers question how well
Players will weather the next economic slowdown or industry
downturn. (It was launched during the biggest casino-industry
boom ever.) Discretionary leisure spending is one of the
first cuts made by consumers in tight times. That could mean
trouble for Players, which depends heavily on membership
renewals.
   At first, the club paid off for Bernard Szynaka, an
engineer from St. James, N.Y., who visited casinos several
times a year. The $29-a-night cost of staying at the Aladdin
in Las Vegas was "like giving it away," he says. He canceled
his membership last month, saying he doesn't plan to gamble
again soon. But he adds that Players' promotions "aren't
quite as good as they were." Lately, he had found new
restrictions, "like no Saturday check-in."
   The company says such cases are the exception and that it
actually has expanded the club's benefits.
   Blaine Warner of York, Pa., a retired 61-year-old former
night-club owner who goes to Atlantic City three times a
month and Las Vegas at least once a year, says, "For me, it's
a good deal because I'm there all the time."
   Some members have complained to local and state
authorities, saying the club doesn't deliver what's promised.
Players says it responds to complaints and none has resulted
in any action against it.
   The club is run from Calabasas, Calif., a Los Angeles
suburb. Edward and David Fishman, the brothers who founded
Players, formerly produced TV game shows. The Fishmans and
other directors own about 53% of the company, which went
public in 1985 by purchasing a public shell corporation.
   "We've got a very specialized niche," says David Fishman.
"Our customers are the ones who usually pay full price for
everything." The average member, according to Players, is
married, 45 to 60 years old, with income of $52,000 and a
per-trip betting bankroll of $1,300.
   Saving a buck isn't the only appeal. "People want to be
recognized," Mr. Fishman adds.
   After a rocky start -- the club attracted only 12,000
members the first year -- Players thinks it has hit a hot
streak. It turned its first profit -- of $509,000, or seven
cents a share, in fiscal 1989, compared with a loss of
$295,600, or four cents a share, a year earlier.
   Players actually bombed in its first direct mailing. "Our
biggest problem was credibility," says Stanley Harfenist,
Players International president. But, after Mr. Savalas --
who is widely perceived as street-smart -- was recruited as
spokesman, members began signing up.
   Although Players found a niche, it is hardly without
indirect competition. "Players Club is one part of a whole
movement toward sophisticated player marketing, and it's
something a lot of casinos are doing very well," says Daniel
R. Lee, an analyst with First Boston Co.
   Some new casino programs are working with Players Club to
attract middle-market gamblers. Such casinos know that
Players has a data base of roughly three million names.
Harrah's Marina casino in Atlantic City, however, is dropping
its contract with Players, saying it can't spare the extra
rooms that the club wants in peak periods.
   Still, Players has more names than members. Then there are
people who never even join; many think they can make better
arrangements themselves.
   Now, though, Players says its biggest worries are about
accommodating members. Says David Fishman, "I'm not lying
awake at night anymore thinking, `Are we going to make it?'"
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
